{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"f6e34a40-44df-11ed-8248-89156b37d550","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"8fec6a34-4d43-4c05-9a44-996737bfdbe4","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Corporate Bond Yields","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"8fa31d18-393d-4dad-ab7b-379f36209c8b"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"c2f3eaf2-d05b-4417-b3af-4e022455ba7f","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"How does the credit risk of default affect bond prices and yields? The cash flows promised by the bond are the most that bondholders can hope to receive. Due to credit risk, the cash flows that a purchaser of a corporate bond actually ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"expects","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" to receive may be less than that amount. For example, GM struggled financially in 2006 and 2007, substantially increasing the chance that they would default on their bonds, and GM subsequently did in 2009. Realizing this risk, investors in GM bonds incorporated an increased probability that the bond payments would not be made as promised and prices of the bonds fell. Because the yield to maturity of GM’s bonds is computed by comparing the (now lower) price to the ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"promised","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" cash flows, the yield to maturity ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"increased","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" as the probability of being paid as promised decreased. This example highlights the following general truths:","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"f1b3960d-8577-4b27-86c6-514851e7dccf"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"1","startValue":1},"ref":"90e85117-31cc-47cd-b3d1-369c285735c1","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"da519264-9128-4797-b5c1-548a9844d586","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"be2fb855-d068-468b-8ac1-a3bb73ea21c0","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Investors pay less for bonds with credit risk than they would for an otherwise identical default-free bond.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"7b8f8f56-3421-4816-a746-c73519e064dc","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"621bb73f-370d-4e3d-9cdf-6e24868978f2","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Because the yield to maturity for a bond is calculated using the promised cash flows instead of the ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"expected","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" cash flows, the yield of bonds with credit risk will be higher than that of otherwise identical default-free bonds.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"9d7ab539-0240-49d4-ac65-5d0205280f4c"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"7810cae2-c974-4789-aee5-0c4bee63e0b4","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"These two points lead us to an important conclusion: ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"the yield to maturity of a defaultable bond is not equal to the expected return of investing in the bond.","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" The promised cash flows used to determine the yield to maturity are always higher than the expected cash flows investors use to calculate the expected return. As a result, the yield to maturity will always be higher than the expected return of investing in the bond. ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Moreover, a higher yield to maturity does not necessarily imply that a bond’s expected return is higher.","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"5871deb2-73d2-45c7-b1de-8aa4b84044ad"}]}]}]}]},"screenType":"","transitions":{"enter":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""},"exit":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""}},"lockElements":false,"learnerCurrentAttempt":1,"footer":{"buttonText":"Next","buttonIcon":"Arrow","showFooter":false,"showHistoryNavButtons":false,"previewFooter":false,"position":"Fixed to screen bottom","footerComponent":{"showFooterDropArea":"hide","width":100,"footerComponentsAlignment":"right"}},"styles":{"background":{},"stage":{"maxWidth":940,"background":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","responsive":true,"padding":{"vertical":60,"horizontal":60},"border":{"color":"rgba(224, 224, 224, 1)","radius":0,"width":0}},"elements":{"padding":{"vertical":10,"horizontal":10}},"footer":{"buttonColor":"rgba(0, 115, 202, 1)","textColor":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)","backgroundColor":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","padding":10,"corners":4,"border":"none","shadow":"0 -1px 4px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.06), 0 0 12px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.1)"},"feedback":{"width":320,"textColor":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)","backgroundColor":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","corners":4,"border":"none","shadow":"0 5px 47px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.15), 0 10px 20px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.1), 0 7px 8px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.1)"}},"title":"Corporate Bond Yields"},"assets":[],"scenarios":[],"pluginPayload":{"pluginRepositoryPath":"https://plugin-repository-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/9417ac60-5f60-1